  "prompt": "What are the best books about the late-80s/90s internet industry leading up to the dot-com bubble?",
  "response": "Here are some highly recommended books about the internet industry during that era:\n\n1. \"The New New Thing\" by Michael Lewis\n- Chronicling the rise of Silicon Valley and the internet boom\n- Focuses on Jim Clark and the entrepreneurial culture of the time\n\n2. \"Burn Rate\" by Michael Wolff\n- A personal memoir about the dot-com era\n- Provides an insider's perspective on the startup culture\n\n3. \"Startup\" by Jerry Kaplan\n- About the early days of pen computing and venture capital\n- Offers insights into the technology entrepreneurship of the period\n\n4. \"Nerds 2.0.1\" by Stephen Segaller\n- Companion book to a PBS documentary\n- Comprehensive history of the internet's development\n\n5. \"The Perfect Store\" by Adam Cohen\n- Detailed account of eBay's founding and early growth\n- Illustrates the e-commerce landscape of the late 90s\n\n6. \"In the Company of Giants\" by Rama Dev Jager\n- Interviews with tech pioneers like Steve Jobs, Bill Gates\n- Provides context for the technological transformation\n\n7. \"Dot.con\" by John Cassidy\n- A critical look at the dot-com bubble\n- Analyzes the economic dynamics and eventual crash\n\nThese books offer different perspectives on the internet industry's explosive growth during that period.",
